ical weapons programme. The interior ministry said former colonel Ahmed Habib Ali, described as an expert in chemical weapons, had been detained on charges linked to the storage of sarin gas and the manufacture of chemical munitions at Unit 417, a facility near Damascus. Officials said Ali oversaw the production of about 20 sarin-filled bombs weighing 250 kilograms each, alleging they were used in attacks carried out against Syrian towns during 2013 and 2017. The detention follows Syria\u2019s recent reinstatement to the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons, after years of suspension over findings that Assad\u2019s forces had used sarin and chlorine gas during the country\u2019s civil war. International investigators have long linked the former government to a series of chemical attacks, including the August 2013 strike on rebel-held suburbs of Damascus that killed more than 1,400 people, according to US intelligence and human rights organisations. Facing the threat of US military intervention, Assad agreed later that year to dismantle Syria\u2019s declared chemical arsenal, although subsequent investigations alleged that prohibited weapons continued to be used. The latest arrest highlights the new government\u2019s efforts to demonstrate accountability for some of the conflict\u2019s gravest alleged crimes while rebuilding ties with international institutions. Authorities have arrested dozens of former Assad-era officials since the former president\u2019s overthrow in December 2024. In April, Syria\u2019s judiciary began public trials against former members of the security establishment, with prosecutors pursuing cases that include alleged war crimes committed during the suppression of the 2011 uprising. The arrest of a senior figure allegedly connected to Syria\u2019s chemical weapons programme is likely to draw close international attention as investigators continue to examine responsibility for one of the darkest chapters of the country\u2019s 14-year conflict. Suggested By Editor Syria regains voting rights at chemical weapons watchdog Suggested By Editor Syria regains voting rights at chemical weapons watchdog", "content": "ONLY AVAILABLE IN PAID PLANS", "keywords": null, "creator": null, "language": "english", "country": ["bahrain", "united arab emirates", "lebanon", "kuwait", "palestine", "syria", "qatar", "egypt", "jordan", "saudi arabia", "tunisia", "libya", "algeria", "morocco", "iraq"], "category": ["world", "politics"], "datatype": "news", "pubDate": "2026-07-16 08:08:51", "pubDateTZ": "UTC", "fetched_at": "2026-07-16 08:40:27", "image_url": null, "video_url": null, "source_id": "thearabweekly", "source_name": "The Arab Weekly", "source_priority": 118009, "source_url": "https://thearabweekly.com", "source_icon": "https://n.bytvi.com/thearabweekly.png", "sentiment": "ONLY AVAILABLE IN PROFESSIONAL AND CORPORATE PLANS", "sentiment_stats": "ONLY AVAILABLE IN PROFESSIONAL AND CORPORATE PLANS", "ai_tag": "ONLY AVAILABLE IN PROFESSIONAL AND CORPORATE PLANS", "ai_region": "ONLY AVAILABLE IN CORPORATE PLANS", "ai_org": "ONLY AVAILABLE IN CORPORATE PLANS", "ai_summary": "ONLY AVAILABLE IN PAID PLANS", "duplicate": false}, {"article_id": "ab5160001e599d16651303288896f1e1", "link": "https://www.elbalad.news/7040156", "title": "\u0627\u0633\u062a\u062b\u0646\u0627\u064a\u0654\u064a ... \u0647\u0627\u0631\u064a \u0643\u064a\u0646 \u064a\u062a\u063a\u0632\u0644 \u0641\u064a \u0645\u064a\u0633\u064a", "description": "\u0627\u0654\u0634\u0627\u062f \u0647\u0627\u0631\u064a \u0643\u064a\u0646 \u0646\u062c\u0645 \u0645\u0646\u062a\u062e\u0628 \u0627\u0646\u062c\u0644\u062a\u0631\u0627 \u0628\u0644\u0648\u0646\u064a\u0644 \u0645\u064a\u0633 \u0642\u0627\u064a\u0654\u062f \u0635\u062f\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0644\u062f : \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0635\u062f\u0631 \u0627\u0633\u062a\u062b\u0646\u0627\u064a\u0654\u064a ... \u0647\u0627\u0631\u064a \u0643\u064a\u0646 \u064a\u062a\u063a\u0632\u0644 \u0641\u064a \u0645\u064a\u